[1] Case update
- Tue 14 Aug 2018. 3 suspected Ebola cases reported in Uganda (Kasese district), one dies: WHO
[Xinhua News Agency, edited]
http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-08/15/c_137390360.htm


The World Health Organization (WHO) on [Tue 14 Aug 2018] said 3 suspected cases of Ebola have been registered in the western Uganda's Kasese district.

WHO in a statement issued here said 2 of the suspected cases are from neighboring eastern Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), where the viral hemorrhagic fever has already broken out, leaving 41 people dead.

The 3rd was a pregnant woman who died at a hospital.

The global heath body said samples from the suspected cases have been taken to the Uganda Virus Research Institute (UVRI) for laboratory tests.

"Two of the alert cases from DRC are alive. They were identified at the Mpondwe screening point with temperatures above 37.9 C [100.2 F] and 38.8 [101.8] respectively, the latter also had a headache," said the statement.

WHO said the 3rd alert case involved a pregnant woman who died at Kaganda hospital due to ante-partum haemorrhage.

"Use of theater where the patient was operated on stopped until it is properly disinfected and the body has been retained in Kaganda hospital pending arrangements for safe burial," said the statement.

The Ebola virus is highly contagious and can cause a range of symptoms including fever, vomiting, diarrhea, generalized pain, and in many cases internal and external bleeding.

Mortality rates of Ebola fever, according to WHO, are high, with the human case-fatality rate ranging from 50 percent to 89 percent, depending on viral sub-type.

